{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617139"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:10:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:10:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16456"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16456"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.05,0.05,0,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9147"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66016"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9147"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51467"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7114"},{"type":"tags","id":"8506"},{"type":"tags","id":"8511"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21725"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21728"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66016"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following mechanisms is most involved in the pathogenesis of vasogenic oedema?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased permeability of capillary endothelium","Decreased osmotic pressure gradient","Obstruction of cerebrospinal fluid flow","Impaired cellular ion transport","Reduced aquaporin-4 expression"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVasogenic oedema is characterised by the accumulation of fluid in the extracellular space of the brain, primarily affecting white matter. The fundamental mechanism involves disruption of the blood-brain barrier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased permeability of capillary endothelium\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism in vasogenic oedema. When the blood-brain barrier is compromised, plasma proteins and fluid can leak into the brain parenchyma causing oedema. This commonly occurs around brain tumours, abscesses, and areas of inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased osmotic pressure gradient\u003C/strong\u003E is more relevant to cytotoxic oedema, which occurs in conditions like stroke or hypoxia, where cellular energy failure leads to accumulation of intracellular fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObstruction of cerebrospinal fluid flow\u003C/strong\u003E leads to interstitial oedema, a different type of brain oedema that occurs due to increased pressure in the ventricular system forcing fluid into the periventricular white matter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpaired cellular ion transport\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily associated with cytotoxic oedema, where failure of sodium-potassium ATPase leads to cellular swelling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced aquaporin-4 expression\u003C/strong\u003E would actually protect against certain types of brain oedema, as these water channels facilitate fluid movement between compartments. Their upregulation, not reduction, is associated with oedema formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment of vasogenic oedema typically includes corticosteroids, which reduce capillary permeability and inflammation, along with treatment of the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vasogenic oedema occurs due to disruption of the blood-brain barrier leading to increased capillary permeability.","Increased hydrostatic pressure and plasma proteins in the interstitial space contribute to vasogenic oedema formation.","Vasogenic oedema primarily affects white matter due to its loose extracellular matrix structure."],"references":["Michinaga S, Koyama Y. Pathogenesis of brain edema and investigation into anti-edema drugs. Int J Mol Sci. 2015 Apr 30;16(5):9949-75. doi: 10.3390/ijms16059949. PMID: 25941935; PMCID: PMC4463627.","Jha SK. Cerebral Edema and its Management. Med J Armed Forces India. 2003 Oct;59(4):326-31. doi: 10.1016/S0377-1237(03)80147-8. Epub 2011 Jul 21. PMID: 27407555; PMCID: PMC4923559.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51467"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16456"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51467"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-28T19:09:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-28T19:10:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9147"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66016"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre